Risk and Crime

1. A map of your outcome of interest in point form, with some description of what, when, and why you think selection bias may be an issue.

Visualizing point data.

Robberies in Chicago do appear to be clustered, and may as a result suffer from spatial bias. In other words, where there are cops there are likely report taken. It’s possible that like with many other kinds of crimes, robberies are reported after the crime has taken place. That means robberies reported are likely a function of the time and interest a victim has in pursuing a report. It may be easier to report a crime to a police officer nearby rather than calling 911 and waiting for a cop to show. Thus, the clustering we see on these first maps may be a product of where police are accesible to the public.
